{root} Beyond any object of focus, the nature of mind is clear.
[Having no path to travel is the start of the path to buddhahood.]
Once you are familiar with the absence of an object of meditation, you attain unsurpassable awakening. (64–66) {/root}

{root} You will live long, have no gray hairs, [[your vitality] increasing like the [waxing] moon.
Your complexion will be radiant and your strength like that of a lion.]
You will quickly attain the common siddhis and reach what is supreme. (108–10) {/root}

The Conduct of Yoginīs states: {50}
What is called “great bliss” is single:
it’s a single mood dancing as many.[7]

I will describe the common process.
By holding the winds,
first there is heat;
second, bliss develops;
and third, nonconceptuality occurs. (202–6)

Completely Radiant is the great bhūmi;
it’s like the maṇḍala of the sun.
Amṛta Radiance is the second;
it is very luminous, like the moon. (259–62)

Sky Radiance is the third;
it is fully present, like the sky.
Vajra Radiance is the fourth;
the light of that bhūmi is mental joy.
Since it unites with the higher samādhis,
it is termed “vajra.” (263–68)

The fifth is called Ratna Radiance;
it is fully present as the bestower of empowerment.
Padma Radiance is the sixth;
it fully arises, like a lotus.
The naturally pure mind-itself
holds what is stainless completely. (269–74)

The seventh is Karma Radiance; {75}
it is said to be the activities of the buddhas.
The eighth is Peerless;
it has no example. (275–78)

Exemplified is the ninth;
everything is understood through examples.
The tenth is Prajñā Radiance;
it is unexcelled buddhahood. (279–82)

The eleventh is Omniscience;
it is fully luminous, the great bhūmi.
The twelfth is the intuitive embodiment of awareness;
it is complete yogic wisdom.[38] (283–86)

When luminosity manifests,
the mind in which the four emptinesses are one[49] {80}
arises unified with illusory wind. (524–26)

Blend winds and consciousness,
the external deity and yourself.
Having exchanged your body, benefit sentient beings. (718–20) {84}

Once you have stabilized transference,
activate your previous habituation[122]
using the characteristics of training in illusions. (943–45)

Transference to somewhere higher is threefold:[16]
using the mode of the generation process,
the actual illusion, and luminosity. (41–43)

Once you have stabilized transference,
strengthen your previous habituation[58]
using the characteristics of training in illusions. (3.60–3.62)

When the confusion of dream experiences occurs,
[imagine] at your throat the letter oṃ with light rays.
Due to the connections between the latent tendencies of recollection and intention,
when you dream of men, they are called male spirits;
when you dream of women, they are called female spirits;
if you dream of animals, those are considered nāgas;
if your dream is happy, your mind is elated;
and when your dream is unhappy, your mind is miserable. (19–26)

Eight doors are the windows to saṃsāra.
One door is the path to mahāmudrā.
Close the eight and open the one. {109}

Having received the genuine guru’s kindness, {110}
[I was shown] the dharmadhātu, illuminating nonduality.
Homage to that sublime path. (5–7)

Release upward like an arrow.
Gradually milk space.[*6] {[*6] The vital points of the objects.}
Cultivate the meditative concentrations of the four cakras.[13]

Although causes and results have not been dual from the outset, {112}
due to the power of thoughts, causes and results appear.
If individuals who lack such realizations[*9] {[*9] Those of future generations.}
take the words alone to be the meaning, they will deceive themselves and others. (91–94)

This is not emptiness,[*10] {[*10] You may ask, “What is emptiness?”} and it is not nonemptiness.[21]
If you ask, “Who has that?”
the perfect buddhas possess it. {113}

Your location won’t be predictable;
you won’t stay forever in one place. {115}
Assemblies of ḍākinīs will gather,
and you will receive prophecies in your dreams. (2.70–2.73)

With these profound instructions of Secret Mantra,
I do not say, “this is a noble view,”
except when referring to the path of method. (2.168–2.170)

Moreover, if you keep three things secret—
first, the yogic practitioner’s body;
second, the dharma;
and, third, the body that gives rise to experiences—that is excellent. (2.224–2.227)

The intermediate Aural Transmission is the Dakpo tradition; however, [this composition] combines the root texts of the Five Cycles, the clarifying manuals, and the customary procedures that are the extensive entrusted transmission of the tantras and esoteric instructions [bestowed] on Mase Lodrö Rinchen, the mahāsiddha of [this] entrusted transmission.
I, a follower of the precious Kagyu tradition, Karma Ngakwang Yönten Gyatso Tinle Kunkhyap Palzangpo, compiled [this text] in the practice place of Śrī Devīkoṭi Tsādra Rinchen Drak during my eighty-seventh year. The secretary was my attendant Losel Sangak Tenzin.
May virtue and excellence increase. {150}

…sparśe vajri…{167}
The vajra goddess of the dharmadhātu holds a source of dharmas.
White,…

Saying hūṃ hūṃ phaṭ phaṭ ha ha with wrath,
you destroy the arrogance of the lions of humans and trample on fear with your feet.
With the sounds of a la la, you subdue all obstructors. {170}

The skandhas and dhātus of those here are the victorious ones, male and female consorts. Among the objects, sense faculties, and mind, the sense faculties [and] objects are the krodhīs [and] heroes. The inseparability of the three existences is offered as the connate yoga.
Thus, offer to the assembly of deities of your own body.
Deities of the maṇḍalas of the four classes of tantras, heroes, ḍākinīs, dharma protectors, and guardians: when I respectfully offer with the stream of amṛta, please grant your blessings through your kindness. {203}

Do whatever liturgy is appropriate for refuge, bodhicitta, and the four immeasurables, which are used in the context of guru yoga.
…abide in the great equanimity.[*2]
To establish all sentient beings, who equal the extent of space, in unsurpassable awakening, I will meditate on guru yoga. {217}

Great bliss vajra:
from the embodiment of great bliss,
please arise as that.

Saying puṣpe, place a flower as the covering top ornament. Throw vase water on the activity vase and, touching it, say:
As long as the activities of the maṇḍala are not completed, turn back the hosts of obstructors.
Having done that, conclude with the offerings and praises. {231}

Next:
In front, from yam, is a blue wind maṇḍala in the shape of a bow and marked by victory banners. Above that, from raṃ, is a red fire maṇḍala, a triangle marked by blazes. On its three sides are oṃ āḥ hūṃ, from which are three hearths of human heads. Above those, from the letter a, is a skull cup, white on the outside, red on the inside, spacious and vast.
Inside that, from oṃ, is a sun maṇḍala. In its center, from mūṃ and go, are urine and cow flesh marked by hūṃ and mūṃ. In the east, from vi and na, are feces and human flesh marked by oṃ and vaṃ. In the south, from ra and ku, are rakta and dog flesh marked by trāṃ and lam. In the west, from śu and da, are bodhicitta and horse flesh marked by āṃ and pāṃ. In the north, from ma and ha, are māṃsa and elephant flesh marked by khaṃ and tāṃ. {264}

The light that radiates from the hūṃs in the hearts of all deities…
Circle the blazing mudrā at your forehead and say: {309}
…and the sound of saying pheṃ pheṃ invoke, from the ocean of the naturally pure realms, Abhirati and the others, the sixty-two-fold maṇḍala of Cakrasaṃvara, support and supported, surrounded by innumerable assemblies of buddhas and bodhisattvas.

Through saying that and conferring the abhiṣeka on my head with the water in the vase, the stains of the three doors of all the deities are purified. My entire body is filled by the stream of amṛta. It rises up and overflows, and swirling at the top of my head, it becomes the lords of the families.
[We, as] the principal male and female consorts are crowned by Vajradhara, male and female consorts. The four inner goddesses are crowned by Ratnasambhava. The deities of the mind [cakra] are crowned by Akṣobhya. The deities of the speech [cakra] are crowned by Amitābha. The deities of the body [cakra] are crowned by Vairocana. The eight female gatekeepers are crowned by Amoghasiddhi. The external deities are crowned by their respective family lords. The abhiṣeka deities dissolve into the crown of their respective family lords.
Thus, contemplate. {311}

With your hands in añjali and holding incense, say:
Guru, the assembly of deities of the glorious Cakrasaṃvara and retinue, please consider me. I, the yogic practitioner called Vajra (insert your name), follow all you, genuine beings. In order to mature beings who are not matured, to free those who are not free, to provide relief to those who have no relief, please enter your disciples into the process of the abhiṣeka. Consider us with your kindness, grant your permission and your blessings.
Thus, having supplicated, feel that you receive permission to inquire about the maṇḍala.[5] With the mudrā of raising up, say: {321}

On the twenty-four spokes of the cakras of the three planes are the assembly of heroes and ḍākinīs, who protect the twenty-four places:
those with blue forms, Khaṇḍakapāla and Pracaṇḍā, and the others;
those with red forms, Aṅkuraka and Airāvatī, and the others;
and those with white forms, Mahābala and Cakravegā, and the others.

In the heart of the ācārya is a hūṃ. You appear clearly as the yidam, and within your empty enclosure, in your madhyamā channel is a blue eight-petaled lotus with a sun, the red dhātu, and a moon, the white dhātu. On those seats appears a clear and prominent thumb-sized samādhisattva Heruka, who resembles yourself and is like the burning iron produced by a blacksmith’s charcoal fire. {352}
From [the hūṃ and the samādhisattva] light rays radiate to the ten directions, invoking the gurus, yidams, buddhas, and bodhisattvas of the ten directions in forms like yourself, seed letters, emblems, and blazing light with the nature of fire. From the principal one of the maṇḍala, innumerable forms like themselves radiate. With crackling sounds and roaring sounds, they all dissolve into the body of the Heruka at your heart. The Heruka is on fire and your body blazes, causing overwhelming bliss to expand.
Thus, contemplate.

